===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|ろく|yomi=goon|alt=六:non-legal}}

Substitute spelling for {{m|ja|六|tr=roku||six}},<ref name="KDJ2-six">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|六・陸}}</ref><ref name="DJR"/> likely borrowed from similar usage of written {{der|ja|zh|陸|tr=-||six}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{ja-pron|ろく|acc=2|acc_ref=DJR}}

====Noun====
{{ja-noun|ろく}}

# {{lb|ja|financial|archaic|sort=ろく}} the number [[six]], [[6]] {{q|used only in legal documents, otherwise {{m|ja|六}}}}

=====Usage notes=====
Legal uses arose due to the relative ease with which certain number kanji can be fraudulently altered to look like other number kanji.  For instance, {{m|ja|一|tr=ichi||one}} could be modified to look like {{m|ja|六|tr=roku||six}}, but it cannot be modified to look like {{m|ja|陸|tr=roku||six|pos=in legal contexts}}.

=====See also=====
* {{m|ja|大字|tr=daiji||big character|pos=more-complicated kanji used as phonetic replacements for simpler numeric kanji, in order to prevent fraudulent modification}}
